ce:section.ce:para:
The Langmuir model quantitatively describes a monolayer adsorbate because it forms on the outer surface of the adsorbent. The development of monolayer adsorbate indicates the conclusion of the adsorption process. Furthermore, the Langmuir model assumes equal energies of adsorption onto the surface where there is no adsorbate transmigration in the surface plane or the inner surface of the adsorbent and can be used to determine the maximum adsorption capacity of a sorbent (Q

                           m
                        ) (Bhatt & Shah, 2015; Vasiliu et al., 2011). Fig. S6a and b (Supplementary data) show the linear plots of the Cr6+ and Co2+ Langmuir models, respectively. Using Eq. 3, the maximum C-dot/ChNC adsorption capacity for Cr6+ and Co2+ was determined to be 155 and 152 mg/g, respectively, which is higher than that of conventional sorbents (Chai et al., 2021).
